            <div class="engArticle">
                <div class="article_txt">
<!--imgtbl_start_1--><div class="article_photo_center"   style="width:548px"><div class="article_photo"><!--imgsrc_start_1--><img alt=" The Coupang logistics center in Bucheon-si, Gyeonggi-do, where a cluster of COVID-19-positive patients have been confirmed. Coupang shut down the center after one of the workers at the logistics center was confirmed to be COVID-19-positive. Yonhap News " src=http://img.khan.co.kr/news/2020/05/27/enkh_yYZIDq.jpg hspace=1 vspace=1 /><!--imgsrc_end_1--><p>The Coupang logistics center in Bucheon-si, Gyeonggi-do, where a cluster of COVID-19-positive patients have been confirmed. Coupang shut down the center after one of the workers at the logistics center was confirmed to be COVID-19-positive. Yonhap News</p></div></div><!--imgtbl_end_1--><br />
<br />
A number of workers claimed that quarantine guidelines were not properly followed at the Coupang Bucheon Logistics Center in Bucheon-si, Gyeonggi-do, where a cluster transmission of COVID-19 was confirmed. As of the night of May 27, 63 cases of COVID-19 were confirmed in connection to the Coupang logistics center.<br />
<br />
A, who works at the Bucheon logistics center said over the phone on May 26, “You can’t say there was ever any physical (social) distancing (inside the logistics center).” Workers including A had their meals close together in the cafeteria--over a hundred workers at any given time--until recently and the center never told the workers to keep a physical distance. A said, “Everyone had to go up to the rooftop on the sixth floor to take the shuttle bus when they got off work, but there are only two elevators, so they were often crowded with people.” He further described, “The stairways are narrow, so contact was inevitable whenever we climbed up or down the stairs.” Over four thousand workers are estimated to be working in this logistics center.<br />
<br />
Another worker, B said, “The environment made transmission inevitable (when a COVID-19-positive case occurred),” and added, “The company provided hand sanitizers and measured our temperatures at the entrance, but that was all.” He claimed that the company failed to disinfect the thermal jackets that the center provided. The Coupang logistics center had a cold storage warehouse where the temperature reached minus 20 degrees Celsius, so the workers wore thermal clothing. But the company never managed the hygiene and had workers share the clothes. B said, “The company never washed the clothes, so they smelled. I used to wonder if it was okay to share the same clothes like that.”<br />
<br />
The center was also criticized for failing to properly respond in the early stages, after the first case of COVID-19 was confirmed at the center. Workers said the company forced them to continue their tasks without releasing any information, such as the places where the confirmed patient had visited. On the afternoon of May 24, B asked the logistics center for information mentioning rumors about a confirmed patient, but he received an answer only a day later. The following afternoon, the company replied, “Employees who can come to work this afternoon (May 25), please reply with ‘afternoon possible.’” B came to work and worked until the center was shut down on the afternoon of May 25.<br />
<br />
Even on the afternoon of May 25, when the center notified workers that the center would be closed, the company maintained its attitude and responded with, “As for the details, the quarantine authorities will take action. We do not have the exact information,” when workers asked, “Tell us where the confirmed person had been,” and “What about the workers who came to work on the same day as the confirmed patient?” Workers who were present this day complained of their frustration saying, “Shouldn’t the company take preemptive measures for its employees?”<br />
<br />
A said, “The tasks are divided according to each floor, but since the sites are always in need of help, workers often move from floor to floor when they work.” He further elaborated, “There are no security cameras to identify the specific movements of the confirmed worker within the center, so workers are naturally nervous that they could have been infected. Yet the center was busy keeping quiet instead of providing relevant information in the initial stage.”<br />
<br />
Jung Eun-kyeong, head of the Central Quarantine Headquarters said, “The virus could have been transmitted in the cafeteria and smoking areas (in the logistics center), where workers could not wear masks, and we believe contact between workers in shuttle buses and worksites could also be points of transmission.” She explained, “We are currently conducting diagnostic tests on over four thousand workers at the logistics center in question.” Coupang said, “The quarantine authorities are currently conducting a detailed investigation and we are fully cooperating. There is nothing we can say before the authorities release the results of the investigation.”<br/><br/><a href="http://news.khan.co.kr/kh_news/khan_art_view.html?artid=202005272106005&code=940100" target="_blank"><img src="http://img.khan.co.kr/spko/khan_eng/btn_eng_trans02.gif"></a>                </div>
            </div>

